### Arrhenius theory of acids and bases

An Arrhenius acid is a substance that produces H\({}^{\pm}\) in aqueous solution.

An Arrhenius base is a substance that produces OH\({}^{\pm}\) in aqueous solution.

\begin{tabular}{l l} _E.g.:_ & HNO\({}_{3}(l)\) + H\({}_{2}\)O\((l)\) & NO\({}_{3}\)(aq) + H\({}_{3}\)O\({}^{\prime}\)(aq) \\ \multicolumn{2}{l}{_Note: H\({}_{3}\)O\({}^{\prime}\) is hydronium ion, which is the same as H\({}^{+}\)(aq)_} \\ \multicolumn{2}{l}{NaOH(s) + aq} & Na\({}^{+}\)(aq) + OH\({}^{\prime}\)(aq) \\ \end{tabular}

\(\bullet\) An acid-base reaction involves the formation of salt and water

### Bronsted-Lowry theory of acids and bases

A Bronsted-Lowry acid is a proton (H\({}^{\pm}\)) donor.

A Bronsted-Lowry base is a proton (H\({}^{+}\)) acceptor.

\begin{tabular}{l l} _E.g.:_ & NH\({}_{3}\)(aq) + H\({}_{2}\)O\((l)\) & NH\({}_{4}\)(aq) + OH-(aq) \\ \end{tabular}

\(\bullet\) An acid-base reaction involves the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.

\(\bullet\) When a Bronsted-Lowry acid (HA) loses a proton, the resulting product (A\({}^{-}\)) is called the conjugate base of HA.

When a Bronsted-Lowry base (B) accepts a proton, the resulting product (BH\({}^{+}\)) is called the conjugate acid of B.
* A conjugate acid-base pair differs by a H\({}^{\pm}\).

