### Uses of Buffer Solutions

Buffer solutions are used in situations where it is necessary to maintain pH.

In many biological systems, a change in pH can have a great effect on the functioning of a cell. Therefore, they are usually buffered.

**Blood buffer system of H2CO3 and HCO3-**

The pH of human blood must be maintained within a narrow range of 7.35 - 7.45. The buffer in blood consists of a mixture carbonates (HCO3-/H2CO3).

The cells in our body produce CO2 as a product of aerobic respiration. CO2 dissolves with water in the blood to form carbonic acid, which dissociates partially to give hydrogen carbonate.

H2CO3 - HCO3 + H+

H2CO3/HCO3- forms a buffer system in blood.

When [H+] in the blood increases (e.g. from the lactic acid which is produced during exercise), HCO3- reacts with H+, decreasing the [H+] and helps keep the pH almost constant.

